In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **Window lifecycle events**. You either subclass `Window` or subscribe to events on it.

**Option 1: Subclass `Window`**

```csharp
public class MyWindow : Window
{
    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnCreated()    { /* was OnStart */ }
    protected override void OnStopped()    { /* was OnSleep */ }
    protected override void OnResumed()    { /* was OnResume */ }
}
```

Then in your `App` class:

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    => new MyWindow(new MainPage());
```

**Option 2: Subscribe to events inline**

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = new Window(new MainPage());
    window.Created  += (s, e) => { /* OnStart */ };
    window.Stopped  += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep */ };
    window.Resumed  += (s, e) => { /* OnResume */ };
    return window;
}
```

**Rough mapping:**

| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window |
|---------------|-------------|
| `OnStart`     | `Created`   |
| `OnSleep`     | `Stopped` / `Deactivated` |
| `OnResume`    | `Resumed`   |

Use `Deactivated`/`Activated` if you need to detect focus changes rather than full background/foreground transitions.
